Complete end to end mobile automation for AI tutor app:
------------------------------------------------------

1️⃣ What is Mobile Automation?
           Mobile automation is the process of automatically validating mobile app flows using
           tools instead of manual actions.

2️⃣ APPIUM EXECUTION FLOW ( ARCHITECTURE ) — STEP BY STEP (ANDROID):
   ----------------------------------------------

Step 1: Write automation code
You write Python automation scripts in PyCharm
You use Appium Python Client APIs

Step 2: Python → JSON conversion
Appium Python Client converts Python commands
Converts them into WebDriver JSON commands
Reason: Appium Server understands only JSON (WebDriver protocol)

Step 3: Appium Server receives commands
Appium Server receives the JSON commands over HTTP
This includes Desired Capabilities during session creation

Step 4: Read Desired Capabilities
Appium Server reads:
platformName
automationName
deviceName
app / appPackage / appActivity

Step 5: Decide the driver
Based on capabilities:
platformName = Android
automationName = UIAutomator2
Appium Server selects UIAutomator2 driver

Step 6: Connect to Android device
Appium uses Android SDK tools
Mainly ADB to:
Detect connected device/emulator
Communicate with device

Step 7: Install UIAutomator2 server
Appium installs:
uiautomator2-server.apk
uiautomator2-server-test.apk
These APKs are installed on the Android device

Step 8: Start UIAutomator2 server
UIAutomator2 server starts running inside the device
It listens for commands from Appium Server

Step 9: UIAutomator2 framework is used
UIAutomator2 server uses:
UIAutomator2 framework
This framework is already part of Android OS / Android SDK
Appium does NOT install the framework

Step 10: Execute automation commands
When you write:
driver.find_element().click()
Flow:
Python script
→ JSON command
→ Appium Server
→ UIAutomator2 Driver
→ UIAutomator2 Server (on device)
→ UIAutomator2 Framework
→ Android OS
→ App UI

Step 11: Response travels back
Result (success/failure) travels back the same path
Your Python script receives the response

Step 12: Session continues or ends
Commands keep executing under the same session
When done:
driver.quit()
Appium stops session and cleans up

🧱 PHASE 1 — MOBILE FUNDAMENTALS:  ( 10–15 core concepts matter for automation )
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
1️⃣ Types of Mobile Applications:
           - Native Apps: Built for specific platforms (iOS/Android) using platform-specific languages.
             Locators used for native apps:   ( 1 to 3 are most used )
            1️⃣ resource-id ✅ (BEST)
            2️⃣ accessibility id (or content-desc) ✅ (VERY GOOD)
            3️⃣ Android UIAutomator (advanced locator)   - used for scroll / Partial_text / Dynamic elements
            4️⃣ class name ⚠️ (Limited use)
            5️⃣ text    - used via XPath and Android UIAutomator
            6️⃣ XPath   - used for complex hierarchies ( text/resource-id/content-desc/contains/multiple_conditions)
            7️⃣ index ❌ (Avoid)


           - Web Apps: Accessible via mobile browsers, built with web technologies.
             Locators used for web apps:   ( 1 to 3 are most used )
            1️⃣ id ✅ (BEST)
            2️⃣ css selector ✅ (VERY GOOD)
            3️⃣ name ✅ (GOOD)
            4️⃣ xpath ⚠️ (FLEXIBLE)
            5️⃣ class name ⚠️ (LIMITED)
            6️⃣ link text ⚠️ (LIMITED)
            7️⃣ partial link text ⚠️ (RARE)
            8️⃣ tag name ⚠️ (VERY LIMITED)

           - Hybrid Apps: Combine native and web technologies for cross-platform compatibility.

2️⃣ APK vs AAB:
    1. We use APK for automation because it is directly installable.
    2. AAB is only a Play Store publishing format, not directly installable for testing.

3️⃣ App Lifecycle (Very Important for Automation):
        🧱 >>>>>
        👉 These states can appear unexpectedly (permission popup, notification, low memory, etc.).
        👉 We may not know exactly when they will happen.
        👉 But in automation, we must handle them properly to avoid test failures.
        That’s why understanding App Lifecycle = stability in tests 🔥
        🔹 Pure App Lifecycle States (Core)
        1️⃣ App launch
        2️⃣ App in foreground
        3️⃣ Permission / popup (Paused)
        4️⃣ App in background
        5️⃣ App killed / crash

4️⃣ Emulator vs Real Device:
        🤖 Automation Industry Practice
        70% execution → Emulator
        30% validation → Real device
        Before release → Always real device

