🧱 PHASE 3 — APPIUM CORE (NON-NEGOTIABLE):
-----------------------------------------
🚀 Topic 1: Driver Lifecycle (Notes)
1️⃣ Session Creation
webdriver.Remote() connects to Appium Server
Desired Capabilities are sent
Appium selects driver (UiAutomator2)
UiAutomator2 server APK installed (if needed)
Session ID is generated
Session becomes ACTIVE

2️⃣ Command Execution Phase
All commands run under same Session ID
Example: find_element, click, send_keys

Commands travel:
Python → Appium Server → UiAutomator2 → Device

3️⃣ new_command_timeout
Defined in capabilities
Example: new_command_timeout = 300
If no command sent for 300 seconds
Appium Server automatically kills session
Next command → invalid session id

Timer runs in: Appium Server
4️⃣ Normal Session Termination
When driver.quit() is called:
Appium sends DELETE /session
Stops UiAutomator2 server
Cleans port forwarding
Frees resources
Session destroyed successfully

5️⃣ Abnormal Termination
Session can die due to:
App crash
Emulator disconnect
ADB crash
Appium server stopped
Timeout
Error seen: invalid session id

🚀 Topic 2: Desired Capabilities (Deep Understanding)
1️⃣ What Are Desired Capabilities?

They are:

👉 Configuration settings
👉 Sent during session creation
👉 Tell Appium how to start automation

They are sent only once — during webdriver.Remote().

2️⃣ Types of Capabilities
🔹 Mandatory (Basic)
platformName
deviceName
automationName
Without these → session won’t start.

🔹 App Related
app (path to APK)
appPackage
appActivity
Tells which app to launch.

🔹 Reset Behavior
noReset
fullReset

Controls app data behavior.
🔹 Stability & Timeout
newCommandTimeout
autoGrantPermissions
Improves stability.

3️⃣ When Are Capabilities Used?
Only during:
POST /session
After session is created →
Capabilities cannot be changed.
If you want to change capability →
You must create new session.

4️⃣ How They Travel
Options object
→ Converted to JSON
→ Sent to Appium Server
→ Driver reads them
→ Driver configures device

🚀 UiAutomator2 Internal Working (Deep)
Very important. Most people don’t understand this properly.

📒 UiAutomator2 — Internal Flow Notes
1️⃣ What is UiAutomator2?

👉 Android automation engine
👉 Built into Android framework
👉 Appium uses it to control Android apps

Appium does NOT control device directly.
UiAutomator2 does.

2️⃣ What Happens During Session Creation?
When session starts:
1️⃣ Appium installs:
uiautomator2-server.apk
uiautomator2-server-test.apk
2️⃣ Appium starts Android instrumentation
3️⃣ UiAutomator2 server runs inside device
4️⃣ Appium forwards a port using ADB
5️⃣ Communication starts between:
Appium Server ↔ UiAutomator2 Server
3️⃣ Command Execution Flow
When you write:
driver.find_element().click()

Flow:

Python
→ Appium Server
→ UiAutomator2 Driver
→ UiAutomator2 Server (on device)
→ Android Framework
→ App UI
Response travels back same path.

4️⃣ Why UiAutomator2 Is Important?
Supports Android 5+
More stable than old UiAutomator1
Supports modern Android features
Handles parallel execution (with systemPort)
5️⃣ What If UiAutomator2 Server Crashes?
Then:
Session becomes invalid
You get invalid session id
Need new session

🚀 Topic 5: Session Crash & Recovery Handling

This is real project knowledge. Very important.
📒 1️⃣ What is Session Crash?
Session crash means:
👉 Appium session becomes invalid
👉 Session ID no longer usable
👉 Commands start failing

Error usually seen:
invalid session id

📒 2️⃣ What Can Kill a Session?
🔹 App Crash
If app crashes → UiAutomator2 loses connection → session dies.
🔹 Emulator Disconnect
If emulator closes → ADB disconnects → session dies.
🔹 ADB Restart
If someone runs:
adb kill-server
Session dies.

🔹 Appium Server Stopped
If you close CMD → all sessions die.
🔹 newCommandTimeout
If no command for X seconds → server kills session.
🔹 UiAutomator2 Crash
If automation engine crashes inside device → session invalid.
📒 3️⃣ What Happens After Crash?
Driver object still exists in Python
But session ID is invalid
Any next command → throws error
Example:
driver.find_element()
→ invalid session id

📒 4️⃣ How Engineers Handle This?

In real frameworks:
✔ Proper logging
✔ Retry mechanism
✔ Recreate driver session if needed
✔ Fail test cleanly (don’t hang)

📒 5️⃣ Interview Important Point
Session is controlled by:
👉 Appium Server
Client cannot recover dead session.
Must create new session.

🚀 Topic 6: Parallel Execution (Very Important)
This is real engineer-level topic.

📒 1️⃣ What is Parallel Execution?
Running multiple tests at the same time
On:
Multiple emulators
Multiple real devices
To reduce execution time.

📒 2️⃣ Problem in Android Parallel
Default:
👉 UiAutomator2 uses a default port (systemPort)
If 2 sessions try to use same port:
❌ Port conflict
❌ Session creation fails
Error like:
Address already in use

📒 3️⃣ What is systemPort?
Each Android session must have:
👉 Unique systemPort
Example:
Device 1 → systemPort = 8200
Device 2 → systemPort = 8201
Without unique systemPort → parallel fails.

📒 4️⃣ How It Works Internally
Appium:
1️⃣ Uses ADB port forwarding
2️⃣ Connects Appium server to UiAutomator2 server
3️⃣ Uses systemPort for communication
If ports clash → communication breaks.

📒 5️⃣ Real Framework Practice
In advanced frameworks:
✔ Dynamically assign systemPort
✔ Map deviceName + port
✔ Use pytest-xdist for parallel

📒 6️⃣ Interview Question
Why does Android parallel require systemPort but iOS doesn’t?
Answer:
Because UiAutomator2 requires separate communication ports.

🚀 Topic 7: WebView / Hybrid App Context Handling
Very important if you test hybrid apps.

📒 1️⃣ What is Hybrid App?
Hybrid app =
👉 Native screens +
👉 WebView screens (HTML + CSS + JS inside app)
Example:
Login → Native
Payment page → WebView

📒 2️⃣ What is Context?
Appium works in different contexts:
Default context:
NATIVE_APP
If app contains WebView:
You will also see:
WEBVIEW_com.package.name

📒 3️⃣ How It Works Internally
When session starts:
👉 Appium starts in NATIVE_APP
If WebView loads:
👉 Appium detects WebView
👉 Uses Chromedriver internally
👉 Creates WebView context

📒 4️⃣ How Engineers Handle It
Steps:
1️⃣ Get available contexts
2️⃣ Switch to WebView context
3️⃣ Perform web automation
4️⃣ Switch back to native

📒 5️⃣ Important Capabilities
Sometimes need:
Correct Chromedriver version
WebView debugging enabled
If versions mismatch → session fails.

📒 6️⃣ Interview Questions
What is context in Appium?
Difference between context and activity?
Why do we need Chromedriver in hybrid apps?
How to switch back to native?


🚀 Phase 4 — Locators Deep Dive (Most Practical & Important)

Xpath using ancestor - (//com.horcrux.svg.SvgView/ancestor::android.view.ViewGroup[@clickable="true"])[2]
Xpath using parent - //com.horcrux.svg.SvgView/parent::android.view.ViewGroup     ( Goes one level up )
Xpath using following or preceding sibling -
                    //android.widget.TextView[@text="or, continue with"]/following-sibling::android.view.ViewGroup
                    //android.widget.TextView[@text="or, continue with"]/preceding-sibling::android.view.ViewGroup
Same parent → following-sibling::
Different parent / nested → following::

new UiSelector() supports many attributes.
Most useful ones:
✔ text()
✔ textContains()
✔ textStartsWith()
✔ resourceId()
✔ className()
✔ description() (content-desc)
✔ clickable(true)
✔ enabled(true)
✔ index() (avoid mostly)
✔ instance() (last option

Wait Statements in Appium:
-------------------------
✅ 1. visibility_of_element_located - Element is visible on screen 👉 Most common in mobile
✅ 2. presence_of_element_located - Element exists in DOM (may not be visible)
✅ 3. element_to_be_clickable    - Visible + enabled
✅ 4. invisibility_of_element    - Wait until element disappears (like loader)

For WebElement state checks, mainly:
👉 is_displayed()   - Checks if element is visible on screen.
👉 is_enabled()     - Checks if element is clickable / enabled.
👉 is_selected()    - Used for checkbox / radio button.
1️⃣ element.text     - title = driver.find_element(AppiumBy.ID, "title_id")
                      assert title.text == "Login or create an account"
2️⃣ get_attribute("checked")  -  checkbox = driver.find_element(AppiumBy.ID, "terms_checkbox")
                                assert checkbox.get_attribute("checked") == "true"
3️⃣ get_attribute("content-desc")
4️⃣ Activity / Package Validation

🔹 Pure App Lifecycle States Handling (Core)
It is the different states an app goes through while running on a mobile device.

🔹 Why we must handle it?
👉 App does not stay in one state.
👉 User actions + OS events change state anytime.
👉 If automation doesn’t handle state change → test fails.
👉 Lifecycle handling = stability + real-world simulation.

Main states:
1️⃣ App launch
2️⃣ App in foreground
3️⃣ Permission / popup (Paused)
4️⃣ App in background
5️⃣ App killed / crash

1️⃣ App Launch
🔹 What is it?
Starting the app process and bringing it to foreground active state.
In App Launch handling, we must consider:
    👉 Cold start
2️⃣ App in foreground  👉 Warm start
3️⃣ Permission / popup (Paused) - Handeled
4️⃣ App in background          - Handeled
5️⃣ App killed / crash         - Handeled

Next block would move into:
5️⃣ Permissions & System Interruptions   ( This is separate lifecycle test )   - Handeled
🔹 What are they?
External OS events that temporarily pause your app:
But full list of possible interruptions:
1️⃣ Notification panel
2️⃣ Incoming call
3️⃣ SMS popup
4️⃣ Low battery alert
5️⃣ Permission popup (already done)
6️⃣ App switch (recent apps)


BOTH
6️⃣ App Crash & ANR ( Application Not Responding ) (Very Important): ( Later we automate via pytest hook.)
In pytest + Appium, when a condition fails and you want to stop the test immediately, you can:
👉 Use assert
OR
👉 raise AssertionError
Both mark the test as FAILED and stop execution.
👉 Screenshot on crash
👉 Capture logcat
👉 Auto-run detector via pytest hook
👉 Retry strategy integration
But core part → Done 💪🚀
